<HEADLINE> Former Editor-in-Chief of Egypt's MENA Dies at 75 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Ibrahim Imam, a former editor-in-chief
of Egypt's official Middle East News Agency (MENA), died on
Saturday at 75.
</P>
<P>
Imam became a teacher of journalism in 1955 after receiving a
doctor's degree at Britain's Birmingham University, MENA reported.
He taught at the Journalism Department of Cairo University's Arts
Faculty.
</P>
<P>
He also worked at MENA for several years until 1965 after he was
at the post of editor-in-chief for three years.
</P>
<P>
From 1972 to 1977, he was the dean of the Department of Cairo
University and took the same post of the Press Department of the
religious Al-Azhar University.
</P>
<P>
He also taught journalism at Libya's Benghazi University and a
number of universities in Saudi Arabia till 1985, and worked as a
visiting scholar at several other Arab universities.
</P>
<P>
His major contributions during his 50-year career in journalism
included the establishment of press departments and faculties of
mass communication in Egypt and elsewhere in the Arab world. He
wrote several books, including one, in English, on journalism and
mass communication.
</P>
<P>
MENA did not mention of what disease Imam died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
