<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Appreciates FAO Efforts to Alleviate Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq appreciates efforts made by the
United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) to alleviate
the plight of the Iraqi people, Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan said here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan made the remarks while meeting the visiting FAO
Director-General Jacques Diouf, who arrived in the Iraqi capital
Baghdad on Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan also criticized the U.S. and British representatives at
the U.N. Sanctions Committee for putting on hold contracts Iraq
signed with other countries to import food, medicine and other
humanitarian necessities within the framework of the U.N. oil-for-
food program, the official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
For his part, the FAO director-general promised that his
organization will continue to make efforts to better implement the
U.N. oil-for-food deal, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
Diouf also met on Saturday with Iraqi Agriculture Minister Abdul
Ellan Hameed and Irrigation Minister Mahmoud Diyab Al-Ahmad, the
INA said.
</P>
<P>
However, the INA report did not say whether they talked about
the killing of FAO staffers in Baghdad Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
A gunman, identified as 38-year-old Fuad Haidar, burst into the
FAO office building in central Baghdad early Wednesday morning,
shot and killed two FAO staffers and wounded several others.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival in Baghdad, Diouf told reporters that he would meet
Iraqi officials to get acquainted with Wednesday's incident.
</P>
<P>
"What happened was a mistake. The criminal (Fuad Haidar) did not
have the intention to kill anybody, but the exchange of fire caused
the casualties," Diouf said.
</P>
<P>
Diouf has made no hints that the tragic incident will affect the
work of the FAO in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The FAO office in Iraq is mainly in charge of the implementation
of the U.N. oil-for-food deal, which allows Iraq to sell limited
amount of oil to buy daily necessities to offset the crippling
impacts of the U.N. sanctions in place since Iraq's 1990 invasion
of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
