<HEADLINE> Syria's Bashar Meets Iraqi Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Syria's anointed new leader Bashar
al-Assad received visiting Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad Said al-
Sahaf and his party on Saturday afternoon, the Syrian Arab News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed bilateral relations as well as the
situation in the Arab world and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Bashar, leader of Syria's ruling Baath
Arab Socialist Party and its presidential candidate, discussed with
al-Sahaf means of boosting bilateral ties as Syria was keen to play
an express role in lifting the United Nations sanctions on Iraq in
place since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Political observers in Damascus said the visit is very important
as it might signal a normalization of Syrian-Iraqi diplomatic
relation, which was severed in 1980 due to Syria's support to Iran
in the 1980-1988 Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
Syria also took part in the multi-national troops that drove
Iraq out of Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries started to improve in 1997
with the opening of joint borders for trade and mutual visits. The
two countries also signed an agreement in 1998 for repairing oil
pipelines from Karkok Oil fields in northern Iraq to Syria's Banias
Port overlooking the Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Iraq sent Vice President Taha Mohyiddin Marouf to Damascus last
month to attend the funeral of late Syrian President Hafez al-
Assad, who died on June 10 at the age of 69. Marouf was the first
senior Iraqi official to visit Syria in two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
