<HEADLINE> UK Government Reveals NHS Reform Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Decisions on hospital closures and
bed reductions in Britain are to be taken by an independent panel
and NHS (National Health Service) managers.
</P>
<P>
BBC quoted Health Secretary Alan Milburn Saturday as saying "
the change would be included in next month's National Plan for the
NHS."
</P>
<P>
Milburn told the annual conference of the NHS Confederation in
Glasgow the aim of the change is to give those who used and worked
in the NHS more power to decide what facilities should be
available within the service.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that the National Plan will propose a"traffic
light" system of ratings for NHS organizations. Each Organization
will be rated green, amber or red.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, high performing green-rated units will
be given extra resources, and greater autonomy over how they are
spent.
</P>
<P>
Red-rated failing units will be given expert advice and support
to help them improve - and if necessary "hit squads" will be sent
in to impose change.
</P>
<P>
Milburn also announced a six-month maximum waiting time from
referral to surgery for cataract patients in 60 areas of the
country, saying "We need shorter waiting times not just for
certain conditions but for all conditions".
</P>
<P>
A guaranteed maximum wait of 18 months for hospital treatment
was no longer acceptable, and efforts must now focus on cutting
waiting times, especially for cancer and heart disease patients,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
