<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF To Condone Part of Honduran Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Press reports from Tegucigalpa received in Mexico City said
that the IMF decision is part of a project for Highly Indebted
Poor Countries (HIPC).
</P>
<P>
Honduran Finance Minister Gabriela Nunez said that the IMF
governing board made official its approval to reduce the payment
of her country's foreign debt service Friday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
She said that the World Bank will decide next week the amount
of reduction it will grant Honduras, which is expected to be 50
percent of the payments the Central American country must make to
the organization.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Interamerican Development Bank (IDB),
the main multilateral Honduras creditor will also approve the
reduction of 50 percent of the service of the debt for an eight-
year term.
</P>
<P>
Nunez said that all these supports help maintain the Honduran
economy afloat and reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
Honduras requested to enter the HIPC after the sweep of
hurricane Mitch in 1998, which caused losses of 5 billion dollars
and thousands of deaths and victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
