<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mauritian Prime Minister Calls on Africa to Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Mauritian Prime Minister
Navichandra Ramgoolam Saturday called on African countries to
unite and mobilize resources for the common good of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Opening the Zambia International Trade Fair in Ndola, capital
of Copperbelt Province, the prime minister said what Africa needed
was stability, peace and unity of purpose.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam said in order to break out of the vicious cycle of
poverty, conflicts and hopelessness that had besieged the
continent, Africans needed to put aside pride and prejudices and
resolve differences peacefully.
</P>
<P>
He said much as it was the duty of Africans to resolve its own
conflicts and problems and that the international community should
commit itself anew to bringing peace to Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam said the growth of the developing countries in Africa
was centered on peace on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Noting that 33 out of 48 developing countries in the world were
from Africa, he said Africa was currently only contributing about
1 percent to global investment and about 2 percent towards
international trade.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramgoolam said that there was a resurgence of hope as
countries in Africa began to cooperate through regional
integration.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, he praised Zambia for its major role in fighting
the abominable racist regime in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's involvement in the liberation of other countries meant
 sacrifice and courage by Zambians, Ramgoolam said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia, through the able chairmanship of President
Frederick Chiluba, was still making frantic efforts to bring peace
to the Great Lakes region and the Democratic Republic of the
Congo.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam said he was pleased to note that Mauritius and Zambia
had shared the same hopes and aspirations and bilateral relations
had continued to grow since 1974.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chiluba expressed the hope that the hosting of this
year's trade fair would result in new investment and trade
opportunities among Zambia, Mauritius and the regional markets of
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) and
Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said Zambia was one of the most liberal economies in
the world.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the liberalization policies of the government,
he said Zambia would be among countries of the COMESA region that
would facilitate zero tariff entry for all imports from COMESA by
October 31 this year when the COMESA free trade is operational.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government was also studying the draft agreement on
the promotion and protection of investment recently submitted by
Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
The draft will likely be concluded at the inaugural session of
the Mauritius-Zambia joint Permanent Commission on cooperation set
for October this year in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said he was optimistic that bilateral cooperation
between Zambia and Mauritius would continue to grow following the
signing of the general agreement of economic, technical and
scientific cooperation in Mauritius on May 20 this year.
</P>
<P>
Zambia was in the process of ratifying this agreement which
offers additional development possibilities between the two
countries in all areas of cooperation and socio-economic activity,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
