<HEADLINE> S. African UDM to Contest Local Govt Elections on Own Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Democratic Movement
(UDM) of South Africa would not affiliate itself to other
opposition parties to contest the local government elections in
November, the party's leader Bantu Holomisa said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The position of our national conference in 1998 was that we
should go it alone in all elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the UDM National Council meeting in the Free State,
Holomisa expressed the confidence that his party would be able to
secure a substantial number of votes.
</P>
<P>
"The breakdown of our demographics suggests that we stand a
good chance to target both rural and urban communities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Holomisa's affirmation that the UDM would not align itself with
another opposition party came in light of this week's merger of
the New Nationalist Party (NNP) and the Democratic Party (DP).
</P>
<P>
The NNP and DP announced that they would contest the local
government elections under the banner of the Democratic Alliance
to present the government with a formidable opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
