<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Raises Oil Output in Line With OPEC Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Oil Minister Bijan Namdar
Zanganeh said here Saturday that Iran has decided to raise its
crude oil output by 104,000 barrels per day as of July 1.
</P>
<P>
Iran is raising its quota based on the agreement reached by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) on June 21,
Zanganeh was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that the output rise would lead to the increase of oil
exports.
</P>
<P>
Oil ministers of 10 OPEC members agreed in Vienna on June 21 to
boost their output quota by 3 percent, or 708,000 barrels, a day as
of July 1. It was the second time in three months that the
organization voted to raise its quota in an effort to bring down
the soaring prices.
</P>
<P>
With the new output rise, OPEC's official quota, not including
Iraq, is now about 25.4 million barrels a day. The cartel pumps
about 35 percent of the world's oil.
</P>
<P>
Iran is the second biggest producer after Saudi Arabia in the
OPEC, with a quota of some 3.6 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
With the new production increase, many believe that the country
is approaching its reported output capacity of about 4 million
barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
But Iran insists that it has enough potential and production
capacity to meet any new quota allocation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
