<HEADLINE> Iranian Court Issues Prison-Term Verdict on Jewish Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran's revolutionary court on
Saturday issued the final verdict for 13 Jews and four Muslims who
had been accused of spying for Israel, the Islamic Republic News
Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Hussein Ali Amiri, head of judiciary of the
southern Fars Province, 10 Jews and two Muslims in the case were
sentenced to different prison terms, while the other five were
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
Asher Zadmehr and Hamid Tefeleen, two main Jewish defendants,
were each sentenced to 13-year terms on charges of forming illegal
group and espionage network and collaborating with Israeli security
service in gathering classified information.
</P>
<P>
The other eight Jews were sentenced to prison terms varying from
four years to 11 years. Two Muslims were sentenced to two-year
terms.
</P>
<P>
The official said that three Jews and two Muslims were acquitted
due to insufficient evidence and documents pertaining to the
charges brought against them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi
on Saturday welcomed the conclusion of the spy case, which had
drawn international concern.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Jews along with the four Muslims were arrested one year
ago in Shiraz, capital of Fars Province. Court hearings for them
started in the southern city on April 13.
</P>
<P>
The arrest and trial of the Iranian Jews sparked protests from
Israel and Western countries who feared that the Jews would be
given the death penalty and demanded that Iran release them. But
Iran insists that the case has nothing to do with religious beliefs
and no foreign country should interfere in its domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Iran has a Jewish community of about 25,000 people, the largest
in the Middle East outside Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
