<HEADLINE> Russian FM, DPRK Leader Discuss Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) leader Kim
Yong Nam discussed here late Friday bilateral relations and the
preparations for Russian President Vladimir Putin's coming visit
to Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov and Kim, president of DPRK Supreme People's Assembly
Presidium, who is the head of state under the country's
constitution,mulled regional and international issues of common
concern and agreed to details of Putin's trip to Pyongyang later
this month, the Russian Foreign Ministry's information and press
department told reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The parties noted that "the inter-Korean summit that took place
in Pyongyang in June was a landmark for the settlement process on
the Korean Peninsula and is giving an impetus to strengthening
peace in the Northeastern Asia," said the department.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov and Kim also exchanged opinions on the prospects of this
process.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov stressed that Russia will continue to support a fruitful
dialogue in the interests of the inter-Korean settlement and
stability and security on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Russian Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov
told a news conference that military cooperation between Russia
and DPRK will be discussed "for the first time in many years"
during Putin's visit in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Kim Yong Nam was making a brief stop in Moscow en route to
Syria,said Russian diplomatic sources. 
</P>
