<HEADLINE> U.S., Puerto Rico Voluntary Workers Arrive in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Vencermos (We Shall Prevail) Brigade is made of more than
60 U.S. citizens, who will remain in the island until July 15,
performing agricultural tasks for free in the company of some 70
Puerto Rican citizens, members of the Juan Rius Rivera Solidarity
with Cuba Brigade.
</P>
<P>
The Venceremos Brigade, whose first trip to Cuba was in 1969,
is considered as the starter of this world movement of volunteers
who every year donate their work to the island.
</P>
<P>
More than 7,000 U.S. citizens have worked as volunteers in Cuba
since the creation of the brigade 31 years ago, without asking the
Department of State permit to travel to Cuba, as established in
the guidelines for the blockade to the island.
</P>
<P>
These U.S. citizens express in this way their disagreement with
the policy of isolation and hostility maintained by Washington for
more than four decades against Cuba.  
</P>
</TEXT>
