<HEADLINE> Ugandans Free to Vote in National Referendum: Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The people of Uganda were able to
vote peacefully and free from intimidation in the referendum held
on June 29 to determine the country's political system, said Canon
Grace Kaiso, national co-ordinator of Non-government-organization
Monitoring Cluster.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Saturday, Kaiso said: "The
NGO observers were generally satisfied with the conduct of the
voting, and the people were free to vote for their chosen
political system, the Multiparty System or the Movement System,
in the referendum throughout the country."
</P>
<P>
The monitoring cluster of the Referendum 2000 NGO Consortium
has monitored the referendum for the last five months. On the
polling day, they deployed 7,213 observers throughout the country
who witnessed voting in 10, 115 of the 16,500 polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement by Donor Referendum 2000 Group said,
"The voting itself appeared to be conducted in a peaceful and
orderly fashion."
</P>
<P>
"The Group has, however, concluded that the referendum campaign
as a whole was not conducted on a level playing field," it said.
</P>
<P>
Resources available to the ruling Movement were substantially
larger than those available to pro-multiparty advocates, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Observers from 15 countries and regional organizations
monitored the polling exercise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
