<HEADLINE> Traffic Accidents Claim over 60 Lives in Ethiopia in One Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Two heavy traffic accidents
occurred successively this week, killing 64 people and injuring a
dozen of others, mass media here reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sixty people were killed Thursday when the bus with 66 people
on board was swept away by floods in the vicinity of Nazareth,
about 100 kilometers south of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred when the bus was in the middle of a
bridge over a river called Mer Merssa, located between the towns
of Welenchiti and Nazareth, witnesses were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A heavy downpour on that day morning resulted in the swelling
of the river and the submersion of the bridge. The driver of the
bus was trying to imitate a heavy-duty truck driver who managed to
cross the inundated bridge, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, the ill-fated bus gave in to the currents of the
flood, and fell on the main course of the river. The vehicle
drifted for more than two kilometers, police said.
</P>
<P>
Seven survivors were initially reported, but one of them died
later while undergoing medication, Radio Ethiopia said.
</P>
<P>
Just one day after the accident, four people were killed and
nine others injured when a truck collided with a passenger bus in
Jimma town, about 250 kilometers southwest of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
All of the killed were passengers of the bus, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
