<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Police Warn Against Post-election Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's police Saturday said they
had arrested more than 50 people in connection with post-election
violence around the country since last weekend's parliamentary
election.
</P>
<P>
This prompted them to issue a warning that people who engage in
 such violence would meet the full wrath of the law irrespective
of their political affiliations.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Police Commissioner Griffiths Mpofu told reporters:
"Police would like to warn that those people who are caught on
the wrong side of the law will be severely dealt with. Political
parties should also encourage their supporters to desist from
political violence."
</P>
<P>
He said the police were on firm ground to deal with any
disturbances.
</P>
<P>
"There are some people who are bent on carrying out the
pre-election excitement to the post-election period," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said this week suspected supporters of the Movement for
Democratic Change (MDC) were alleged to have barred market
supplies at Mbare Msika, accusing the farmers from rural areas of
betrayal since the ruling Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) won most of its seats in the rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
In the tightly contested parliamentary election, Zanu-pf won by
a majority of 62 of the 120 seats followed by MDC with 57 seats
and then Zanu (Ndonga) with one seat.
</P>
<P>
At least 30 people were killed in political violence
countrywide in the run-up to the election. 
</P>
