<HEADLINE> Lebanese Court Ends Trial of Bin Laden Followers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese military court on Friday
night concluded the trial of 29 alleged followers of Saudi-expelled
billionaire terrorist Osama bin Laden on charges of planning
attacks on U.S. and Israeli targets in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Two of the accused were sentenced to five years in jail and the
others, including Lebanese, Egyptian and Syrian defendants, were
given jail terms of one year or less. Some were tried in absentia,
including an Egyptian who was sentence for life.
</P>
<P>
According to the list of charges, the accused had planned to
carry out attacks on orders from bin Laden. "They formed a group
aimed at committing crimes against people, trying to carry out
terrorist acts, forging passports and using them, counterfeiting
foreign currencies and transferring weapons and ammunition without
licenses," it said.
</P>
<P>
The trial in Beirut coincided with court proceedings in Jordan,
where 28 suspects are being tried on similar charges.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden is on the list of the most wanted by the United
States, which accused him of masterminding the 1998 bombing of two
U.S. embassies in East Africa, killing more than 200 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
