<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows How Red Wine Fights Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. researchers have revealed
the mechanism of how an antioxidant found in red wine and grapes
fights cancer.
</P>
<P>
The compound resveratrol, which acts like antibiotic to protect
grapes from fungus, may turn off a protein that enables cancer
cells to survive even chemotherapy, said the researchers with
University of North Carolina Medical School.
</P>
<P>
Experiments showed that when the protein was blocked in mice,
the cancer cells were eradicated by the chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
The findings were published in the July issue of Cancer
Research.
</P>
<P>
"The benefit is that it certainly provides an open door for
potential therapies," said Minnie Holmes-McNary, the study's lead
author. That may include taking a pill similar to vitamin
supplement.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, a University of Illinois researcher reported
resveratrol's link to red wine and fighting cancer. Resveratrol
also blocked cell inflammation, which is linked to arthritis and
other diseases.
</P>
<P>
Resveratrol exists in dozens of foods, including mulberries and
peanuts. All wines have some resveratrol but red wine seems to be
its richest source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
