<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, July 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Eight people were crushed to death and three were
injured late Friday at an outdoor rock music festival in Denmark,
media reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The disaster occurred just before midnight on Friday when a
huge crowd pressed forward against the main stage during a
performance, reports quoted Danish police sources as saying on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Police sources were quoted as saying that the victims, all men,
were pressed up against the barriers in front of the stage by an
enthusiastic crowd during a concert performed by the U.S. band
Pearl Jam.
</P>
<P>
The dead were yet to be identified and they there was no
information on the nationalities of the casualties. (Denmark-
Concert-Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan's Chief Executive General Pervez
Musharraf Saturday ruled out instituting a treason case against
ousted prime minister Nawaz Sharif for his statement about last
summer's Kargil conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Nawaz Sharif will not be tried on sedition charges for his
statement on the Kargil issue. If the matter is taken to the
court, many national secrets will be exposed," Musharraf said in a
press talk after inaugurating a highway project in Balochistan
province.
</P>
<P>
"It is surprising how Nawaz Sharif talked about this issue. I
will neither respond to these statements nor will we institute any
case against him as it will affect the national security," the
chief executive said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, in a speech last month, said he was kept in dark about
the Kargil operation which had led to the one-month long fighting
between Pakistan and India along the Line of Control in the
disputed area of Kashmir last summer.
</P>
<P>
The then prime minister demanded formation of a high-powered
commission to probe into the episode.
</P>
<P>
On June 22, a Pakistani citizen named Arif Noor filed a
petition to the Lahore High Court seeking registration of treason
case of Sharf for "leaking state secrets" to the public. However,
the petition has not yet been accepted by the court.
</P>
<P>
Sharif has been sentenced to life imprisonment in a hijacking
case and is being tried in a corruption case. (Pakistan-Sharif)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GUANGZHOU -- The death toll from an explosion at a fireworks
factory Friday morning in Jiangmen, south China's Guangdong
Province, has risen to 36, and 160 others have been reported
injured, according to latest reports.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 people are still missing following the blast,
which investigators believe may have occurred when sparks produced
by employees pounding iron nails ignited inside the warehouse
building, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The explosion at 8:05 am Friday at the fireworks factory built
in 1992 by Jiangmen Local Product Export Company leveled the 3,200-
sq-m factory, and blew off roofs, shattered windows and collapsed
walls of buildings up to one kilometer away, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the injured were wounded by flying debris, according to
doctors in local hospitals. (China-Fireworks Explosion-Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Two reformists, Elias Hazrati and Ali Akbar
Mohtashamipur, won the runoff election for the sixth Iranian
Majlis (parliament) held in Tehran constituency on Friday, it was
announced here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The other two candidates, Ali Akbar Rahmani and Rasul
Montajabnia, also reformists, failed to get enough votes to enter
the parliament, the Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Interior
Ministry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tehran constituency has a share of 30 seats in the 290-seat new
parliament. The two newly elected reformists joined 26 others who
made their way into the parliament in the first-round election
held on February 18.
</P>
<P>
Two seats in the constituency, the political center of the
country, went to the hands of the conservatives in the first-round
election, including former president and parliament speaker
Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
But the senior politician, believed to be a member of the
conservative establishment, has refused to take his seat in the
parliament and his substitute is to be elected through a by-
election. (Iran-Tehran-Election) 
</P>
