<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government has asked the World Bank (WB)
to increase the technical assistances provided by the WB to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The WB is currently financing many projects in Jordan, including
reforming of the public sector, privatization, anti-poverty, and
supporting the private sector, particularly in tourism and in the
export-oriented sectors.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman's Magid Elfatim company said it plans to build a
commercial, tourist and recreational complex in the country at a
cost of over 30 million Omani rials (79 million U.S. dollars),
covering an area of 150,000 square meters. The work in this complex
will be completed within 15 months starting August.
</P>
<P>
The company also plans to expand its operations in Egypt, Syria
and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The volume of Japan's exports to the United Arab
Emirates in 1999 witnessed an 11.6-percent decline from 2.85
billion U.S. dollars in 1998 to 2.52 billion dollars, according to
statistics released by the Dubai-based Japan External Trade
Organization (Jetro).
</P>
<P>
Electrical machinery, transport equipment and textiles were the
major categories that suffered a decline in Japanese exports to the
UAE last year.
</P>
<P>
"This decline can be attributed to market sluggishness that
prevailed in the re-export markets of the UAE due to a general
slump in the price of crude oil during the preceding years," a
newsletter of Jetro said.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus and Sri Lanka Friday signed a cooperation
agreement in the shipping field.
</P>
<P>
The agreement provides for cooperation in employment issues, the
improvement of sailors' working and living conditions and the
acceptance of certificates issued by each country.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for cooperation in the case of nautical
accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
