<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Reformists Won Tehran Runoff Election for Majlis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Two reformists, Elias Hazrati and Ali
Akbar Mohtashamipur, won the runoff election for the sixth Iranian
Majlis (parliament) held in Tehran constituency on Friday, it was
announced here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The other two candidates, Ali Akbar Rahmani and Rasul
Montajabnia, also reformists, failed to get enough votes to enter
the parliament, the Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Interior
Ministry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tehran constituency has a share of 30 seats in the 290-seat new
parliament. The two newly elected reformists joined 26 others who
made their way into the parliament in the first-round election held
on February 18.
</P>
<P>
Two seats in the constituency, the political center of the
country, went to the hands of the conservatives in the first-round
election, including former president and parliament speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
But the senior politician, believed to be a member of the
conservative establishment, has refused to take his seat in the
parliament and his substitute is to be elected through a by-
election.
</P>
<P>
Friday's election in Tehran actually could not change the new
political balance in the new parliament, which has managed to start
work on May 27 after overcoming all kinds of obstacles set up by
the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Reformers supporting President Mohammad Khatami control some 80
percent of the seats in the new parliament. The reformist victory
in February's election was seen as a great push to the country's
reformist movement growing since Khatami took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, a number of the seats in the new parliament are still
vacant due to the cancellation of partial election results by the
Guardians Council, which is among one of the many major state
organs still in the hands of the conservatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
