<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Trace of Missing Indonesian Ferry Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Hopes of finding a missing
Indonesian ferry were dashed Saturday after sighting of the ship
turned out to be false, according to the Antara News Agency
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Saturday, Antara quoted Indonesian Director of Sea
Transportation Tjuk Suhardiman as saying that the ferry ran
aground on an island about 80 mile off the northern coast of North
Sulawesi province.
</P>
<P>
But a fly-over by the Indonesian Navy turned up nothing.
</P>
<P>
"We spotted a ship from the air, but it wasn't the missing
ferry," Commander Djoko Sudarman, head of the search and rescue
operation, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ship, Cahaya Bahari, left Tobelo on Halmahera in North
Maluku province on Wednesday en route to Manado, capital of North
Sulawesi. Radio contact with the vessel was lost after its captain
M.M. Paparaga radioed an "SOS" advising that the ship was taking
water in fast during a violent storm at noon on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But rescuers were puzzled that they have found no debris or
other signs of a sinking.
</P>
<P>
Antara quoted some sources as saying that the ferry had been
taken hostage in Morotai island in North Maluku province.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's SCTV television channel correspondent reported from
Manado that the navy and rescue team would fly to Morotai to check
the report.
</P>
<P>
There is conflicting data about the total number of passengers
on board as the Cahaya Bahari was licensed to carry only 270
people. The National Search and Rescue Agency claimed that at
least 492 passengers, refugees from Maluku and crew may have been
aboard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Scholars Demand Fair Resolution of "Hanaoka Incident" Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Japanese scholars and activists from
civic groups attending a symposium in Odate, Akita Prefecture in
northeastern Japan, urged Saturday the Japanese judicial
authorities to bring about a justice end to the lawsuit relating
to the "Hanaoka Incident."
</P>
<P>
The symposium was held at the Labor and Welfare Hall in Odate
city as part of a series events marking Friday's 55th anniversary
of the "Hanaoka Incident" in which some 130 forced Chinese
laborers in Japan were slaughtered during an uprising at the end
of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Japanese scholars and lawyers who have consistently supported
surviors of the Chinese laborers' bid to seek fairness from
competent Japanese authorities, such as Shigeyuki Kawada, Hiroshi
Tanaka, Takashi Nimi and Shuichi Adachi, delivered speeches at the
symposium, disclosing some historical facts on Japan's past
aggressive war against China and briefing on the current
development of the "Hanaoka Incident" lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
They also urged the Tokyo High Court to speed up efforts to
resolve the lawsuit which demands apology and compensation for
Chinese surviors and relatives of the victims in the incident.
</P>
<P>
On June 30 1945, more than 700 Chinese laborers forcibly
brought to Hanaoka town by Japanese aggressor troops in China,
angered at the hard labor, launched an uprising. The upring was
later suppressed by Japanese military police and more than 130
laborers were killed in the incident.
</P>
<P>
On June 28, 1995, 11 surviors and relatives of the victims in
the "Hanaoka Incident" filed a lawsuit with the Tokyo District
Court, demanding the court to fairly resolve issues such as
compensation pending between Chinese surviors and Japan's
construction firm Kajima, which used the Chinese laborers at that
time.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo High Court put forward a "reconciliation advice" to
both sides in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, some 200 people, including officials from the
Chinese Embassy in Japan, Odate municipal government officials and
representatives of local civic groups, attended a ceremony held in
Hanaoka town to commemorate the 55th anniversary of the "Hanaoka
Incident." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Result of Sweden vs China Table Tennis Friendly </HEADLINE>
