<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 36 Killed, 160 Injured in Fireworks Explosion in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from an explosion
at a fireworks factory Friday morning in Jiangmen, south China's
Guangdong Province, has risen to 36, and 160 others have been
reported injured, according to latest reports.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 people are still missing following the blast,
which investigators believe may have occurred when sparks produced
by employees pounding iron nails ignited inside the warehouse
building, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The explosion at 8:05 am Friday at the fireworks factory built
in 1992 by Jiangmen Local Product Export Company leveled the 3,200-
sq-m factory, and blew off roofs, shattered windows and collapsed
walls of buildings up to one kilometer away, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the injured were wounded by flying debris, according to
doctors in local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The factory, leased in December 1993 to be run by the Hong Kong
Overseas Oriental Fireworks Company, has reported several fires in
its short history. On April 4, local fire departments urged the
factory to improve its fire-fighting and alarm systems and to
strengthen management, but the order was ignored.
</P>
<P>
After the accident, provincial leaders including Governor Lu
Ruihua rushed to the scene to oversee rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
An emergency meeting was held today by the Guangdong provincial
government to order all fireworks factories and manufacturers of
cigarette lighters in the province to suspend production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
