<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Greets Upsurge of Returned Students (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 students who have
returned to China after going to school abroad today signed
contracts with domestic enterprises at the 2000 China Liaoning
Week for Enterprises of Overseas Scholars and Forum of Science and
Technology, which started here June 29.
</P>
<P>
The contracts, involving 130 million U.S. dollars in total,
cover several areas in the high-tech industry including electronic-
information, bio-engineering, energy-saving and environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
The forum attracted 370 students, mostly Ph.D.s, returning from
24 countries and regions. They brought over 500 high-tech projects
for cooperation to the fair, which was organized by the ministries
of Education, Science and Technology and Personnel and Liaoning
Provincial People's Government.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Minister of Science and Technology Xu Guanhua said
this year's forum was much bigger than the previous two, both in
scale and in the number of signed contracts.
</P>
<P>
Ma Yanhui, who holds a Ph. D. in medical science, said, "Now is
a golden time for Chinese students who have finished their studies
abroad to go back to the motherland and build up their own careers.
"
</P>
<P>
Ma, 40, enrolled in a U.S. graduate school in 1987. After
graduation, he remained in the U.S. to conduct research on
diabetes, and set up his own pharmaceutical company in Silicon
Valley in 1997. Ma came back China to set up two pharmaceutical
companies for producing artificial insulin pumps he had developed
in Tianjin and Shenyang in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government supports students going abroad, and
encourages them to make contributions in their homeland after they
have completed their schooling. Between 1978 and 1999, 320,000
Chinese students and scholars had gone abroad to study -- double
the figure of the previous 100 years. Of these students, 110,000
have returned to China and in turn supported China economic and
cultural development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Greets Upsurge of Returned Students (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Present-day China provides a favorable environment for
returned students. After two decades of reforms and opening-up,
the country is enjoying brisk economic growth, long-term social
stability and an improved investment climate," Xu Guanhua said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that returned students have a decided advantage
over foreign entrepreneurs doing business in China because they
have gained new technological and managerial expertise, keep
abreast of new development of international market, and understand
Chinese customs.
</P>
<P>
Wang Baisong, 45, who came back to China after earning a Ph.D.
in the United States, said that the two eye clinics he opened in
the U.S. sell only four or five pairs of reading glasses a month,
while his shop in the Dalian High-tech Development Zone has sold
hundreds of the same types of glasses daily since it opened in
June last year.
</P>
<P>
"China has a big market and numerous opportunities. I am
optimistic about future development in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
China greeted the first wave of returned students in the 1950s.
Many returnees have made tremendous contributions to the
motherland and are now noted scientists.
</P>
<P>
Qian Lingxi, an 84-year-old academician at the Chinese Academy
of Sciences who returned from Belgium in the 1930s, said, "We came
back to meet the national crisis before new China was founded. The
returned students of today came back to revitalize the country."
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin said in an interview with the
American magazine "Science" in May that China is taking steps to
create better working and living conditions, and establish a more
flexible mechanism to attract talented Chinese students in school
abroad to come home.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has built 53 state-level and high-tech
development zones in Beijing, Tianjin and Xi'an, in which 32 high-
tech parks for returned students were established. The combined
annual industrial and trade profits of these parks increased from
8.7 billion yuan in 1991 to 670 billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province, the only technical innovation experimental
zone in the country, plans to allocate 200 million yuan in each of
the next five years to support high-tech projects launched by
returned students, said Zhang Guoguang, governor of Liaoning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
