<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Station Named After Dunhuang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A railway station on the Lanzhou-
Xinjiang railway line today was named after Dunhuang, a world
heritage site in northwest China's Gansu Province, with the
approval of the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
The station, originally known as Liuyuan Railway Station, is an
important passage from inland areas to Qinghai, Xinjiang, Tibet
and Gansu in northwestern China.
</P>
<P>
It is also the destination leading to the Mogao Grottoes in
Dunhuang, which were included on the World heritage list in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1958, the station has played a significant role in
transporting tourists to Dunhuang. Some 530,000 Chinese and
foreign tourists visited historic site last year.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 100th anniversary of the discovery of the
Dunhuang cave which contains thousands of centuries-old documents
and relics. The city of Dunhuang is hosting a series of activities
to mark the event.  
</P>
</TEXT>
