<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Iranian Jews Convicted of Spying for Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Ten Iranian Jews Saturday were
sentenced to prison terms of four to 13 years on charges of spying
for Israel, while three others were acquitted, the Islamic Republic
News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Hamid Tefeleen, the main defendant among the 13 Iranian Jews
arrested in March 1999, were sentenced to 13 years in prison, his
lawyer Shirzad Rahmani told IRNA in Shiraz, capital of the southern
Fars Province, where the verdict was issued.
</P>
<P>
"The verdict issued by the court is unfair and my client has not
had any activity in the espionage network," Rahmani said, insisting
that the court lacked any evidence for its verdict.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, head of the provincial judiciary chief Hussein Ali
Amiri said that the 10 Iranian Jews and two Muslims accused of the
same crimes were sentenced by the revolutionary court. The
punishments included jail terms, whipping and cash fines.
</P>
<P>
He said that the other three Jews, who had been out on bail
since February, and two other Muslims were acquitted, adding that
the final 71-page verdict on the case would be made public later in
the day.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Jews along with four Muslims were arrested last year in
Shiraz, more than 800 kilometers south of the capital of Tehran.
Court hearings for those accused started in the southern city on
April 13. In all, eight defendants had confessed to passing on
classified information to Israel and having links with Israel's
security service, four had pleaded innocent, and one acknowledged
passing information but insisted that his action did not constitute
espionage.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, there has been debate in Iran about
whether the Jews would be sentenced to death, with the judiciary
officials divided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The arrest and trial of the Iranian Jews sparked protests from
Israel and Western countries who demanded Iran to release them. But
Iran insists that the case has nothing to do with religious beliefs
and no foreign country should interfere in its domestic affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Fighting Claims 48 Lives in northern Sri Lanka  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's government troops have
killed 38 Tamil Tiger rebels but lost 10 soldiers in fresh
fighting in the north of the country, a government statement said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Over 30 rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
including two leaders were killed Friday when troops launched an
operation to attack and destroy a rebel strong point at
Ehthawetunuwewa in the northern Welioya regions, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
It said nine soldiers were killed and 43 others wounded in the
operation.
</P>
<P>
In the northern Jaffna peninsula, troops killed eight LTTE
rebels but lost one soldiers in separate confrontations, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels are fighting for a separate homeland called
Eelam for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
More than 60,000 people have been killed in the long-running
ethnic conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
