<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia, Angola Agree to Improve Common Border Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia and Angola Saturday agreed to
 intensify cooperation to improve deteriorating security situation
along their common border.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique issued here at the end of the
four-day session of the Zambia-Angola Joint Permanent Commission
on Defence and Security, the commission reviewed and deliberated
on the general security situation in the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) region and particularly the security
situation along the common border between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The commission expressed concern over the deteriorating
security situation along the border and appointed a technical
committee comprising officials from both countries to investigate
the incidents and report back to the commission.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to establish permanent communication
links between the regional commanders and other security chiefs in
the border provinces of Moxico and Cuando-Cubango of Angola and
Zambian border provinces of Northwestern and Western.
</P>
<P>
Such communication links will be complemented by intensified
border patrols, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
On Angola, the commission applauded the gains so far made by
the government in the offensive against the rebel National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) led by Jonas Savimbi
and expressed the hope that the protracted conflict in Angola will
end soon.
</P>
<P>
The commission hailed the end of the fighting between Rwandan
and Ugandan troops in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
city of Kisangani and subsequent withdrawal of these troops from
that area.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the commission called on the United Nations to
hasten the deployment of the full compliment of military observers
and peacekeepers in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
On Zimbabwe, the two sides welcomed the recent peaceful conduct
of the parliamentary elections and expressed solidarity with the
Zimbabwean government in its initiatives aimed at equitably
distributing land among its citizenry.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Defence Minister Chitalu Sampa and Home Affairs
Minister Peter Machungwa as well as their deputy ministers
attended the meeting. Angola Interior Minister Fernando Dos Santos
and Deputy Defence Minister Armando Neto also attended the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
In March this year Zambia deployed more troops in its
Northwestern Province bordering Angola to check the area which had
been attacked persistently by armed personnel suspected to be
Angolan rebels. Angola once repeatedly accused Zambia of allowing
its territory to be used to transport military and logistical
supplies to UNITA but the latter denied the accusation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Rocket Carries U.S. Satellite Into Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A Russian Proton-1 carrier rocket
Saturday successfully sent a U.S. commercial satellite SD-RADIO
into a planned orbit, the press service for the Russian Aerospace
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The rocket fired off from the Baikonur cosmodrome in
Kazakhstan at 2:09 a.m. Moscow time (2309 GMT Friday).  The
satellite was put by a Russian rocket-space transport system into
an optimum geo-stationary orbit with a height of 47,102 kilometers
and an inclination of 63.4 degrees, at 4:34 a.m. Moscow time (0134
GMT) Saturday, said the press service.
</P>
<P>
The spacecraft has already been separated smoothly from the
platform, and the satellite will further be positioned with its
own engines.
</P>
<P>
It was the 275th launch of a Russian Proton carrier rocket.
</P>
<P>
The SD-RADIO satellite is designed to perform high-quality
radio transmission to mobile radio-receivers. It will also
provide automobile satellite communication on the continental part
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The satellites of this type weigh about 4,000 kilograms and
their construction provides for 100 relaying channels.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Krunichev Space Center has signed a contract for
two other launches of the Sirius-type satellites scheduled for
August and October of 2000, said the press service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
