<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Legitimizes Traditional Chinese Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has recognized
the legitimacy of the traditional Chinese medicine, Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister of Public Health Korn Dabbaransi announced
here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The government has ruled that the traditional Chinese medicine
is a legal and widely-accepted medicine science and treatment," he
said at the annual meeting of the Thai-Chinese Health Cooperation
Committee, which is held here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was based on the satisfactory result of past five
years' trial of standard medical services of the traditional
Chinese medicine, which was conducted with the cooperation of Thai
and Chinese medical institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenkang, Chinese health minister who led a Chinese
medicine delegation attending the meeting, welcomed the move as a
"wise decision."
</P>
<P>
"The preservation and promotion of the traditional medicine now
is a common opinion of most countries in the world," he remarked,
"and Thailand showed its respect to the science and the will of
its people by making this decision."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated China's firm support to help Thailand to develop
a center of study, education and treatment of traditional Chinese
medicine in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
With the traditional Chinese medicine becoming legal in
Thailand, the Ministry of Public Health is now passing a
regulation on licensing of traditional Chinese medicine, Korn
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The applicants for the temporary traditional Chinese medicine
license, which will be valid for two years, must pass professional
and ethical training and the evaluation of the Traditional
Medicine Committee, he stated.
</P>
<P>
With a large number of applicants expected, the official said
the evaluation must be strict, in order to prevent unqualified
persons to conduct traditional Chinese medicine in the country.
</P>
<P>
Another problem is the standardization of traditional Chinese
medicine.
</P>
<P>
Xie Qiangming, a Thai Chinese and one of the first four Thai
doctors who got the license of traditional Chinese medicine, told
Xinhua at the meeting that there are still lots of improvements
for traditional Chinese medicine to achieve in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"Until now, many Thai people think that a doctor of traditional
Chinese medicine can treat any disease, and this need to be
changed, "he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, by imposing certain regulations, traditional
Chinese medicine in Thailand will become more standardized and
specialized, just like modern western medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
