<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Claims Picasso's Missing Painting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has applied to the Turkish
Foreign Ministry for the return of Pablo Picasso's famous
painting "La Fermiere," reported Turkish Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait claimed that the painting was stolen from the Kuwaiti
Palace during the 1991 Gulf War, triggered by Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Turkish police seized two of Picasso's oil paintings, "La
Fermiere" and the "Dora Maar" in two separate raids in the
country's southwestern city of Izmir in May.
</P>
<P>
Pablo Picasso (1881-1973), a Spanish painter, moved to settle
down in Paris in 1904 and later became a leading painter of French
modernist school.
</P>
<P>
"La Fermiere," a portrait of Madame Putman painted in France in
1908, and the "Dora Maar," a portrait of Picasso's Yugoslavian
lover painted in 1938, were smuggled by Syrian and Turkish
nationals through Syria to Turkey to be sold in Izmir.
</P>
<P>
Izmir, Turkey's third largest city, is located at the end of a
smugglers' route coming from the Middle East to Europe because of
its seaport. It is also in close proximity to Greek islands.
</P>
<P>
Police initially stated that the two paintings were not
registered on the list of stolen paintings of the International
Criminal Police Organization (Interpol). However, a stamp from a
French museum on the back of the "Dora Maar," and a stamp from
Kuwaiti Palace on the back of "La Fermiere" raised a question
whether they are original or not.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Interpol said in a later statement that this "La
Fermiere" was registered in St. Petersburg's Hermitage Museum and
is claimed to have been stolen during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
But experts say that "La Fermiere" is definitely original and
has Picasso's signature on the back.
</P>
<P>
Police in Izmir hence issued a statement that the painting
stolen from the former Soviet Union during the Second World War was
Picasso's "Farmer Wife," not "La Fermiere."
</P>
<P>
Now that if "La Fermiere" proves to be the original, Turkey will
have to surrender it to Kuwait because stolen art should be given
back to its rightful owner according to international practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Ranks Third in Oil Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)held
a proven recoverable oil reserve of 97.8 billion barrels at the end
of 1999, third largest in the world, according to the latest BP
Amoco annual statistical review of world energy.
</P>
<P>
UAE's oil reserves accounted for 9.4 percent of the total global
proven oil reserves, said the review.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia with 263.5 billion barrels, or 25.5 percent of the
global total, and Iraq with 112.5 billion barrels or 10.9 percent
of the total are ranked as the two leading oil reserve holders.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, with 96.5 billion barrels, or 9.3 percent of the total,
holds the fourth place, followed by Iran (89.7 billion barrels, or
8.7 percent), according to the review.
</P>
<P>
In all, the Arabian Peninsula, Iraq and Iran have proven
reserves of 675.6 billion barrels or 65.4 percent of the world
total.
</P>
<P>
The UAE alone has more reserves than any of the other
geographical regions into which the BP Amoco review divides the
globe, said the review.
</P>
<P>
"North America (63.7 billion barrels), Central and South America
(89.5 billion barrels), Europe (20.6 billion barrels), the former
Soviet Union (65.4 billion barrels), Africa, including North Africa
(74.9 billion barrels) and Asia and the Pacific (44 billion
barrels)," the review added.
</P>
<P>
UAE's total proven recoverable reserves remained unchanged at
the end of last year from the end of 1998, despite a year of
production, according to the figure cited in the review. "This is
ascribed to the proving of new reserves during the year."
</P>
<P>
One of the key objectives of the exploration strategy of UAE's
oil companies is the delineation and proving of new reserves to
replace those produced.
</P>
<P>
Over the last decade, this strategy has paid off handsomely,
with total reserves declining only slightly from 98.1 billion
barrels at the end of 1989 to 97.8 billion barrels at the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
At the rate of production last year, the UAE has sufficient
reserves to allow for production at the same level for over 100
years, one of only three countries in this position, the report
said. The other two are Iraq and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Proven reserves are defined by the review as being those, which,
with reasonable certainty, can be recovered in the future from
known reservoirs under existing economic and operating conditions.
</P>
<P>
They take no account, therefore, of possible future advances in
recovery techniques.
</P>
<P>
UAE's total daily production last year was 2.505 million
barrels, the review said, a decline of 8.7 percent from the
previous year, and accounting for 3.2 percent of global production.
</P>
<P>
Among those, 345,000 barrels a day were consumed locally, with
the remainder being available for export, the review added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
