<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Hits Japan's Izu Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A strong earthquake measuring 6.1 on
the open-ended Richter scale jolted the Izu island chain south of
Tokyo on Saturday afternoon, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Japan Broadcasting Corp. (NHK) quoted an official at the isle
of Kozushima as saying that one person is feared to have been
buried by a landslide triggered by the quake, which occurred at 4:
02 p.m. (0702 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Power outages affected much of Kozushima, and water pipes burst
in some places, the NHK said.
</P>
<P>
The quake may cause some movement in the surface of the sea but
there is no danger of tidal waves, reported the Meteorological
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake was estimated to be about 10
kilometers below the seabed in the Pacific off Kozushima and
Niijima isles, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
A series of moderate to strong quakes hit several islands in
the island chain early in the day.
</P>
<P>
About 2,600 of Miyakejima's 3,800 residents were evacuated
during the week to safer parts of the island for fear of a
volcanic eruption, but the agency said recent quakes were not
directly caused by volcanic activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
