<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Sees Poor Economic Performance in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkey posted a 4.2 percent growth in

gross national product (GNP) in the first quarter of 2000, while
the figure stood at 8.7 percent in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, gross domestic product (GDP) growth was put at 5.6
percent, while the figure was 9.1 percent in the first three months
of 1999, according to provisional figures issued recently by the
State Institute of Statistics (DIE).
</P>
<P>
Although both GNP and GDP growth rates have beaten the
expectations that centered on 3.5 percent, the GDP growth is
regarded by economists as a poor performance, saying that the
outlook on the production front was not bright despite a pent-up
consumer demand, Turkish Daily News reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"GDP growth could have been 1 to 1.5 percentage points higher if
it was not for a restriction on building licenses," said Faruk
Selcuk, professor of Economics at Bilkent University.
</P>
<P>
Building licenses dropped by 60.4 percent in the first quarter,
according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
The government has projected a GNP growth of 5.5 percent for
2000, following a record 6.4 percent contraction in 1999, when the
economy bottomed out due to the impacts of Russian financial crisis
and a major earthquake that hit Turkey's industrial heartland.
</P>
<P>
Altug Karamenderes, an economist with Ata Securities, said
that "overall the growth performance is quite poor because one
would expect the economy to have achieved the level in 1998, yet
figures remained considerably below that."
</P>
<P>
Selcuk said that "there is a misconception that the economy is
overheating in a way that would fuel inflation."
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that the Turkish economy has considerable room
to grow without causing inflation, adding that a GDP growth of 6-7
percent for the whole year would not fuel inflation, but only match
the 1998 levels.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government targets a 5.5 percent growth in the
economy in 2000 within the framework of a three-year stand-by
package of 4 billion U.S. dollars with the International Monetary
Fund (IMF), approved last December.
</P>
<P>
Ankara also plans to reduce the country's chronic inflation
rate, 65.8 percent in February, to 20 percent by the end of this
year, 10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
