<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubber Goods Promise to Become Bangladesh's Big Export Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Local entrepreneurs see an immense
scope for locally manufactured rubber goods in the world markets.
</P>
<P>
Rubber could be one of the bigger export sources in the country
like garments and frozen foods if proper incentives were available,
the New Nation said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But the quality, not the quantity, of local rubber remains the
main problem in developing rubber-based industries. Leading
entrepreneurs of rubber-based industries have had to import the
raw rubber they need just to ensure the quality of products.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the import spending for
rubber and rubber goods was over 44 million U.S. dollars in 1998-
99.
</P>
<P>
Mubash Shar, senior vice-president of Dhaka Chamber and
Managing Director of Emen Rubber Products Limited, was quoted as
saying that the country needs to form a rubber board, comprising
people from public and private sectors, to allot lands to growers,
determine price of rubber as per international price levels and
monitor quality.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 200 small-scale industries are producing
rubber products, including beach sandals, tubes, shoe soles and
spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Local rubber industries consume around 6,000 tons of raw rubber
annually, excluding best-quality imported variety, leaving some 1,
800 tons surplus.
</P>
<P>
Roughly 7,800 tons of rubber is extracted annually from gardens
in the country. It was projected that some 20,000 tons of raw
rubber would be surplus by the year 2007 after meeting the
domestic demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
