<HEADLINE> Indonesian Missing Ferry Found: Antara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's missing ferry had been
seen and the passengers were believed to be safe, the Antara News
Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Antara quoted Indonesian Director of Sea Transportation Tjuk
Suhardiman as saying that the ferry ran aground on an island about
80 mile off the northern coast of North Sulawesi province.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Indonesian Navy had sent planes and
ships to the island to check reports a missing ferry carrying
hundreds of passengers and Maluku refugees had been sighted.
</P>
<P>
The search had now been switched to Siau island off North
Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, the focus of the search has been shifted to Siau
island because the Navy has received information from the Customs
Office that they have sighted the boat," said Lieutenant Colonel
Sudarsoni, a naval intelligence officer in Manado, capital of
North Maluku.
</P>
<P>
The ship, Cahaya Bahari, left Tobelo on Halmahera in North
Maluku province on Wednesday en route to Manado, capital of North
Sulawesi. Radio contact with the vessel was lost after its captain
M.M. Paparaga radioed an "SOS" advising that the ship was taking
water in fast during a violent storm at noon on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There are conflicting data about the total passengers on board
while the Cahaya Bahari was licensed to carry only 270 people. The
National Search and Rescue Agency claimed that at least 492
passengers, refugees from Maluku and crew members may have been
aboard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
