<HEADLINE> Imported Duty-free Maize Arrives in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- some 1,500 tons of maize from South
Africa has arrived at Kenya's Indian Ocean port Mombasa since the
government waived a 25 to 50 percent tariff on maize early this
month.
</P>
<P>
More imports are expected following reports that Kenya's relief
stocks have been dwindling to less than 60,000 bags from the
beginning of June, Daily Nation newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, about 860,000 bags of maize were bought for drought
relief. It is estimated that more than three million Kenyans
are in desperate need of food assistance compared with 961,000 in
1992, the last time when the east African country experienced a
severe drought.
</P>
<P>
The number of the drought victims could rise dramatically to 23
million, about 80 percent of the country's population, if the
short rains fail in September.  
</P>
