<HEADLINE> Jews Convicted in Iran for Spying 1st lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Ten of the 13 Jews tried on charges
of spying for Israel have been sentenced to fines, lashes and jail
terms while the other three acquitted, a senior judicial official
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hossein Ali Amiri, the provincial judiciary chief of Fars
province where the trial has been held, did not elaborate on the
sentences, the state-run Tehran television reported.
</P>
<P>
Two Muslim suspects, who were also involved in the spying case,
have also been acquitted, but another two Muslims were given
sentences similar to the Jews, Amiri said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Jewish community have been greatly disturbed by the case
while the United States and Israel have been closely following its
development.
</P>
<P>
Both Israel has denied the accused Jews and Muslims are its
agents.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the Jews have pleaded guilty, four have pleaded
innocent and one acknowledged passing information but maintained
his
action was not a constitute espionage.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Jewish community is the Middle East's largest outside
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Bids Farewell to Economic Crisis by Yuan Li </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Just prior to the third anniversary
of the eruption of the Asian financial crisis, Thailand heard one
after another good news assuring of its economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
On June 19, Thailand formally "graduated" from the three-year-
old International Monetary Fund (IMF) supported program. The
executive board of the IMF hailed the country's recovery as "
impressive" so far.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the National Economic and Social Development
Board (NESDB) of Thailand revised its growth projection for the
year to five percent, up from 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Three days later, influential U.S. credit rating agency Moody's
Investors Service announced that it had upgraded Thailand's
sovereign credit rating to investment grade from "junk" status,
citing the country's broad economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said all of these news indicate that Thailand is now
on track for economic recovery after three years of hardship.
</P>
<P>
On July 2, 1997, the decision by the Bank of Thailand to give
up its currency pegging system triggered the collapse of the baht
and brought down with it many currencies in the region, thus
touching off a full-scale financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
With the aid of the 17.2-billion-dollar IMF rescue package and
after the adoption of numerous reform measures, the Thai economy
recorded a 4.2 percent growth last year after a 10.2 percent
shrink in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The NESDB said it revised its growth projection for the year
because of the country's impressive economic growth in the first
three months, which reached 5.2 percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
Among growth sources in the first quarter, exports -- a main
driving force of the country's economic growth -- topped the list
with 25.2 percent growth, followed by combined investment in the
government and private sectors of 17.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government think-tank and planning agency said it has also
revised its export growth projection for the year to 12 percent
from the previous 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing also grew 9.5 percent across the board with
rising exports and stronger domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The strong global demand for computers helped put integrated
circuits and electronic parts at the top of Thai exports. Gains
were also shown in the auto, petrochemicals, steel, jewelry and
textile industries.
</P>
<P>
Low interest rates, the continued fiscal stimulus program and
slight gains in consumer confidence helped boost domestic
consumption, with department store, car and motorcycle sales, and
value-added tax collection all posting gains.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales grew 62.1 percent in the first quarter from the year
before due to the stronger domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Private investment also increased sharply by 14.6 percent year-
on-year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the brighter macroeconomic picture, economists agree
that Thailand still faces many challenges to sustain the recovery.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda, the finance minister, admitted recently
at a seminar that the Thai economy would require at least another
year before recovering to pre-crisis levels.
</P>
<P>
"We must accept reality. While recovery has been steady, it has
not yet reached all sectors," Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
Among the main economic concerns are the level of the non-
performing loans (NPLs) of the banking sector, the weakness of
agricultural commodity prices and the overhanging glut in the
property sector.
</P>
<P>
With the NPLs level in the Thai banking sector remaining
stubbornly high, at more than 37 percent of total loans at the end
of the first quarter, many analysts expressed cautious optimism
that the worst might be over.
</P>
<P>
The property sector, the biggest recipient of credit from the
financial sector, remains weak, as increases in demand remain
insufficient to absorb supply.
</P>
<P>
While the agricultural production has been high, commodities
prices have fallen by about 30 percent in U.S. dollar terms over
the past year.
</P>
<P>
External factors, such as global oil prices and the overheating
U.S. economy, will also play significant roles in the pace of
Thailand's recovery.
</P>
<P>
Another major uncertainty is in the political arena. The
current government must call a general election by November, and
questions remain about whether the new government would continue
carrying out reform policies.
</P>
<P>
The new government will face hard decisions on public debt
management, state enterprise privatization and fiscal stimulus
policies amid tighter budget constraints. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
