<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Government Grants Credit to Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Samurdhi Banks have
granted credit amounting to 16.8 million U.S. dollars to the poor
to launch self-employment projects to raise their income level,
the official Daily News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The banks which set up by the government in 1995, had granted
this amount of credit to more than 257,800 poor families by the
end of March 31 this year, Youth Affairs, Samurdhi and Sports
Minister S. D. Dissanayake was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the newspaper Friday that the banks have thus
become the country's key provider to the poor in the island.
</P>
<P>
The banks issue loans up to a maximum of 330 dollars to each
poor family recipient to embark on ventures to augment their
income,the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sri Lankan Samurdhi Authority will provide credit
facilities through a special fund to low-income families seeking
loans exceeding 330 dollars. A 15-percent interest is charged on
these loans, he added.
</P>
<P>
At present at least 1,000 Samurdhi Banks have been established
in Sri Lanka by the government since 1995 as the key credit
facilitator of the poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
