<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Ranks Second in IDUs in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- There are 20,000 intravenous drug
users (IDUs) in Nepal, the second highest in Asia after India,
according to Nepali health experts.
</P>
<P>
"Among 50,000 drug abusers in Nepal, there are almost 20,000
IDUs,of which 40.4 percent are HIV-positive," said Dr. T. N.Jha,
director of the National Center for AIDS and STD (sex transmitted
diseases) Control, at a workshop on IDU that began here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Intravenous drug use has played a critical role in fueling an
HIV epidemic in Nepal in the past six years," said Jha. "IDUs are
more prone to HIV infection because they directly exchange
syringes and needles among their peer group."
</P>
<P>
"It is estimated that there are 10,000 HIV-positive drug
abusers all over Nepal, a majority of whom share needles without
hesitation due to lack of money," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is projected that if the increasing trend of HIV-positive
and drug abusers is not checked immediately, there will be at
least one HIV positive in each household on average in two years,
said a paper presented at the workshop.
</P>
<P>
Youth Power Nepal, the organizer of the two-day workshop, came
to the conclusion after need assessment among drug abusers that
their needs include free treatment, education and counseling,
methadone treatment, employment, cooperation and affection from
family and society and checkup in public hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The experts at the workshop called for coordination between
private and governmental bodies to help drug abusers return to
normal life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
