<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Closes National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid officially closed the 15th National Games (PON) in Surabaya,
capital of East Java, on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very proud of the organizers and the loyalty shown by all
provinces toward this country during the event. When this nation
is in crisis and our unity is threatened, athletes can still
manage to attain their highest achievements," the president was
quoted by national newspapers Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Host East Java clinched its victory after winning 132 golds,
107 silvers and 115 bronzes. Jakarta, which has always been the
overall champion since the seventh PON in 1969, succumbed to the
runner-up position by earning 116 golds, 85 silvers and 96 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
The next PON will take place in Palembang, South Sumatra, in
2004.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indonesian Olympic Committee Chairman Wismoyo
Arismunandar applauded a flurry of record breaking in the
weightlifting competition at PON.
</P>
<P>
He said that the success was praiseworthy and hoped that the
athletes would be able to carry on their impressive performance to
the sporting arenas at an international level.
</P>
<P>
The weightlifting competition saw 20 national records shattered.
Meanwhile in powerlifting, in which the athletes lift the dead
weight, the record improvement was even more amazing -- 30
national records, 8 Asian records and 2 world records.
</P>
<P>
The new world records were made by Marlina and her male
compatriot Sutrisno, both from Lampung province.
</P>
<P>
The weightlifting competition offered a total of 39 gold medals
-- 15 in weightlifting, 16 in powerlifting and 8 in body-building.
</P>
</TEXT>
