<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Economic Indicators Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economic indicators
continued improving despite a slight drop in non-oil and gas
exports, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS).
</P>
<P>
The monthly inflation rate jumped by 0.5 percent in June, down
from the 0.8-percent increase in May while the year-on-year
inflation in the month was 2.14 percent as compared with 2.86
percent in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Kusmadi Saleh from the BPS said that the rise in the June
inflation was mostly contributed by an increase in food prices.
</P>
<P>
"After the increase in electricity rates, elements of the food
price index that had previously been negative have all turned
positive now," Kusmadi was quoted by The Jakarta Post Saturday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
BPS said price increases for foodstuffs reached 0.16 percent
with those for meat rising by 4.41 percent, the highest level
recorded in the food category.
</P>
<P>
Kusmadi said that with the January to June inflation rate
already reaching 2.86 percent, it was unlikely that this year's
inflation target of 5 percent could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
He said the August general session of the People's Consultative
Assembly and the upcoming hike in fuel prices in October are
likely to further boost inflation.
</P>
<P>
BPS recorded a decline of 2.94 percent in total exports in May
to 4.8 billion U.S. dollars from 4.9 billion dollars in April.
</P>
<P>
The drop was triggered by a decline of 3.99 percent in non-oil
and gas exports to 3.8 billion dollars in May from 3.9 billion
dollars in April.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas exports rose by 1.3 percent due to soaring crude
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Imports rose by 1.15 percent to 2.355 billion dollars in May
from 2.329 billion dollars in April.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus in May rose 18 percent to 2.47 billion
dollars from 2.1 billion dollars in May last year, but dropped
from 2.66 billion dollars in April.
</P>
<P>
"Our industries are already too dependent on imported raw
material, an increase only shows that production is improving,"
Kusmadi said.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that if the rupiah continued to depreciate
it would adversely affect the ability to purchase the products by
these industries.
</P>
<P>
BPS also reported that tourist arrivals in May dropped by 11.5
percent to 298,815 people from 337,818 in April.
</P>
<P>
However, between January and May this year, tourist arrivals
rose by 3.16 percent compared with the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
