<HEADLINE> Manila Extends Deadline for Peace Deal With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government agreed
Friday to extend a June 30 deadline it had set for the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) to forge a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Press Secretary Ricardo Puno said the MILF, which
failed to meet the deadline set by President Joseph Estrada, was
given another 30 days to sign an interim agreement, according to
local press reports Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Although President Estrada has yet to formally extend the
period of of negotiations until July 29, talks will continue, said
Puno, who is also the presidential spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon said the government would not
close the doors on the MILF just because the deadline had passed.
</P>
<P>
Both sides had tried to reach an interim agreement on the
sidelines of the four-day foreign ministers' meeting of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) which ended in the
Malaysian capital of Kuala Lumpur on Friday.
</P>
<P>
But the MILF balked at government conditions requiring the
rebels to first drop their demand for independence, stop terrorist
activities and lay down their arms.
</P>
<P>
Manila rejected a resolution passed by the OIC meeting Friday
demanding that it halt military offensives against the MILF in
Mindanao in the southern Philippines, but welcomed an OIC plan to
send a probe team to Mindanao to determine the real situation
there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government forces launched a final push on the
MILF headquarters, Camp Abubakar, unleashing ground and air
bombardments on it, as the June 30 deadline passed unobserved.
</P>
<P>
The military has claimed that some 5,000 rebels, or one-third
of the rebel force, have been killed and some 40 rebel camps
overrun since government troops launched sustained offensives
against the MILF early this year in Mindanao, where more than 500,
000 civilians have reportedly been displaced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
