<HEADLINE> Ethnic Albanian Boy Attacks KFOR Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A 14-year-old ethnic Albanian boy
blew up a stronghold of the international peacekeeping force in
Kosovo (KFOR) Wednesday, injuring a peacekeeper, said a KFOR press
release issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
KFOR arrested the boy the same day, who admitted that he had
thrown a bomb at the stronghold, said a Yugoslav news agency
Tanjug report based on the press release.
</P>
<P>
Following the explosion, KFOR tightened security around all
strongholds and intensified inspection of vehicles and pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
Violence against non-Albanians, and recently against
peacekeepers also, has occurred continuously in this Yugoslav
province ever since the Kosovo War ended June last year.
</P>
<P>
Escalating friction between ethnic Albanians and peacekeepers
are believed to be related to the recent discovery of huge arms
depots in central Kosovo and subsequent demolition of them by the
KFOR.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, over 1,000 ethnic Albanians protested at the KFOR
actions, waving banners saying "These weapons belong to ethnic
Albanians" and "KFOR out of Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, KFOR troops destroyed anti-tank rockets,
mortars, machine guns and tens of thousands of grenades found near
the village of Klecka in central Kosovo. 
