<HEADLINE> Ukraine Urges U.S. to Extradite Lazarenko </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
Friday criticized the United States for refusing to send former
Ukraine premier Palvo Lazarenko back to Kiev for trial.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday, Lazarenko, detained in a federal prison in
San Francisco since February 1999, was convicted of money-
laundering by a Swiss court and given a 18-month suspended prison
term.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma had repeatedly asked Washington to send back Lazarenko,
who is also on charges of misappropriating state property, abuse
of power and murder of a member parliament.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine was ready to sign "any agreement regarding this problem
" with the United States, the Interfax News Agency quoted him as
saying. The two countries have no extradition treaty.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said that Washington has undermined trust in its
willingness to promote the worldwide fight against corruption by
refusing to send Lazarenko back.
</P>
<P>
"What kind of trust would our society have for the American
legal system, which has been keeping Lazarenko in the United
States for a year and half now?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
"If Lazarenko had no money, he would have been thrown out of
America," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko, 47, Ukraine's first deputy prime minister since
September 1995 and prime minister from June 1996 to June 1997, was
arrested in Switzerland in December 1998 as he entered on a
Panamanian passport.
</P>
<P>
After being indicted by a Geneva judge on charges of money-
laundering, he was released after paying a 3 million U.S. dollars
on bail. In February 1999, he was detained by U.S. immigration
authorities at New York's John F. Kennedy airport for visa
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
A wider investigation in America charged Lazarenko with
laundering 114 million dollars allegedly stolen while in office.
Earlier this month, Lazarenko had once again pleaded not guilty to
these charges.
</P>
<P>
Under the American legal system, the case will be handled in
the United States and Lazarenko's illegal property will be
confiscated.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko had fought extradition, saying he would not get a
fair trial in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
However, earlier this week, Lazarenko admitted that he funneled
9 million dollars in stolen money through Switzerland and a Swiss
court had confiscated 6.6 million from his Swiss bank accounts.
The funds will be eventually restituted to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Swiss prosecutors believed that he has stolen a total of 880
million dollars from Ukraine between 1994 and 1997, with more than
170 million passing through Switzerland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
