<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Epidemic Threatens San Francisco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
San Francisco, known around the world as a gay capital, became
one of the first centers of the Acquired Immune Deficiency
Syndrome epidemic in the early 1980s, when as many as half the gay
men in the city were believed to be infected with HIV. Since 1981,
more than 18,000 San Franciscans have died of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Quick action by the city's gay community and public health
officials also made San Francisco a model for the fight against
AIDS, pushing new HIV infections down from an estimated high of 6,
000 in 1982 to a fairly steady 500 per year during 1990s.
</P>
<P>
City health officials, however, now estimate that, after years
of relative stability thanks to aggressive prevention programs,
safer-sex publicity and new drug treatments, new HIV infections in
San Francisco doubled to 900 in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The estimated total for 2000, however, is between 800 and 900,
with gay men accounting for about 575 of the new HIV infections,
Dr. Willi McFarland of the city's Department of Public Health said.
</P>
<P>
The latest released statistics show that, 1.3 percent of all
gay and bisexual men who were anonymously tested at San Francisco
clinics were diagnosed as HIV positive in 1997. That rose to 2.6
percent in 1998 and 3.7 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We see in San Francisco what is going to happen next in the
epidemic. We saw the first AIDS infection, and now we're seeing
the first rise in new infections," Dr. Thomas Coates, director of
the AIDS Research Institute at the University of California-San
Francisco, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We think this needs to be a wake-up call for the rest of the
nation," said Dr. Ronald Valdiserri, deputy director of the
National Center for HIV, STD and TB Prevention at the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
Local doctors said the soaring rate of HIV infection, while
alarming, is no surprise. They have tracked a similar rise in
risky behavior as new AIDS drugs have made the disease seem less
threatening.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of gay men in San Francisco who reported always
using a condom during sex fell from 70 percent in 1994 to 54
percent in 1999, and the proportion who said they had unprotected
anal sex with more than one partner grew from 23 percent in 1994
to 43 percent in 1999, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
About 40,000 new HIV infections are reported each year in the
United States, with gays and bisexuals accounting for 40 percent
of that.
</P>
<P>
The figures were released in advance of the International AIDS
Conference, set for July 9-14 in Durban, South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000701.0170 </DOCNO>
