<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Trace of Survivors Found in Indonesian Ferry Sinking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian rescuers are still
struggling Saturday to find any survivors or wreckage from the
wooden-hulled Cahaya Bahari ship in the stormy waters of North
Sulawesi Province.
</P>
<P>
However, rescuers returning from search operations have
reported no trace of the ship or any other scattered items such as
baggage or wreckage of the ship, which left Tobelo on Halmahera in
North Maluku Province Wednesday en route to Manado, capital of
North Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
Radio contact with the vessel was lost after its captain M.M.
Paparaga radioed an SOS advising that the ship was taking in water
fast during a violent storm at noon on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to national newspapers Saturday, at least three
warships and a ship belonging to the search and rescue team have
been scouring the area where the ferry sank about 64 kilometers
off the northern coast of North Sulawesi, 2,300 kilometers
northeast of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying our best to locate the ship. The search will
continue as it is still unclear whether the ship has completely
sunk," Udianto, the administrative chief of the North Sulawesi
Ministry of Communications Office, was quoted by The Jakarta Post
as saying.
</P>
<P>
A navy reconnaissance plane and an air force helicopter were
also conducting an aerial search.
</P>
<P>
"We looked from the air and there was nothing to be found.
Usually when a boat goes down there is debris and bodies floating
in the water," Commander Djoko Sumaryono, head of the search and
rescue effort, told The Indonesian Observer.
</P>
<P>
Heavy seas, low cloud cover and strong tidal waves reaching
three meters high were hampering the search. A ferry of this kind
rarely comes equipped with adequate life jackets or lifeboats.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers said hopes of finding any survivors were fading.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a miracle if we find anyone still alive," head of
the Manado Search and Rescue Office Soleman told the Antara News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
There is conflicting data about the total number of passengers
on board as the Cahaya Bahari was licensed to carry only 270
people. The National Search and Rescue Agency claimed that at
least 492 passengers, refugees from Maluku and crew might have
been aboard.
</P>
<P>
In Manado Port, hundreds of anxious relatives sat waiting for
news of their loved ones. They swarmed the port soon after news
broke that the ship had gone missing on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
