<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major science stories released by Xinhua this week:
</P>
<P>
 China to Start Gene Sequencing of Pigs
</P>
<P>
China will start a gene sequencing project to upgrade breeds of
pigs and promote studies on xeno-transplantation and biological
drugs, said a Chinese scientist in Beijing on June 29.
</P>
<P>
This is a follow-up to Chinese scientists' successful
completion of one percent of the sequencing of the human genome,
said Zhang Meng, a spokesman of the Human Genome Research Center
of the Genetics Institute, the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that though Germany, Denmark and other European
countries have already started similar joint research projects,
Chinese scientists see greater potential in their own undertaking.
</P>
<P>
 China Sets up New Cellular Engineering Institute
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an Cellular Engineering Project Development Center was
officially inaugurated on June 29 in this capital of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province. The state-designated institute is
expected to invigorate China's bio-engineering research.
</P>
<P>
Jointly founded by the No. 4 Medical College of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army and the Shaanxi New and High-Tech
Industries Investment Co., the center will focus on the study of
engineering development of animal cells, cross-breeding tumor
cells, cellular-engineering and cell factor tests.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Scientists Hails Mapping of Human Genome
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have highly praised the completion of the
working draft of human genome map, which was accomplished by
scientists from six countries and announced on the Internet Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very important scientific result, which can help human
beings know more about themselves and how to treat and prevent
some major diseases," said Yang Huanming, director of the Human
Genome Research Center of the Institute of Genetics of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have completed their share of the
international research project -- one percent of the sequencing of
human genome -- ahead of the schedule, said Lu Yongxiang,
president of the CAS, adding that this shows Chinese scientists
are at the forefront of life science research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
