<HEADLINE> Wimbledon Warning for Star's Dad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Jelena Dokic's father Damir will be
banned from Wimbledon if there is any repeat of his misbehavior,
the All England Club has warned.
</P>
<P>
Dokic was led away by police on Thursday after an incident when
he smashed a journalist's mobile phone and uttered drunken rants
against the Women's Tennis Association.
</P>
<P>
The police decided not to take any action against Dokic, who
also fell foul of the law at Edgbaston last year.
</P>
<P>
But an All England Club spokesman said: "Following discussions
with the WTA Tour, in the light of yesterday's incident we will be
monitoring the conduct of Mr Dokic closely."
</P>
<P>
"Should this again fall below acceptable standards it would
lead to Mr Dokic being banned from the grounds."
</P>
<P>
WTA Tour chief executive officer Bart McGuire backed the move,
saying: "If future disruptions occur on the site during this
tournament we would support the Club's removal of Mr Dokic from
the grounds."
</P>
<P>
He added that the WTA will be looking at the incident
separately and did not rule out further action being taken.
</P>
<P>
Dokic, 17, came through a doubles match today with Jennifer
Capriati, beating Conchita Martinez and Patricia Tarabini 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards she implored the Wimbledon authorities not to block
access to her father.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslavia-born Australian said: "I have a great
relationship with my dad. He's always been with me and is a big
influence on me and my tennis. I like having him around."
</P>
<P>
"He knows my game more than anyone else, he's someone I can
work with. He's always on the court with me, we do things together.
Parents and the family are the biggest support you can have."
</P>
<P>
The incident yesterday culminated in her father shouting that
the WTA were run by "criminals and fascists". He was escorted to
the police office clutching a flag of St George.
</P>
<P>
In Birmingham last year he was thrown out of the DFS Classic in
Edgbaston for making too much noise. He was then arrested by
police for lying down in the road.
</P>
<P>
During the Australian Open in January he was involved in a
scuffle with a camera crew. 
</P>
