<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Condemns Angolan Rebels for Continuing War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Friday strongly accused the
rebel National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
of violating peace agreement and continuing war in Angola.
</P>
<P>
At the closing session of a five-day meeting of the
Angola-Zambia Joint Permanent Commission on Defense and Security,
Zambian Defense Minister Chitalu Sampa said "the current situation
of conflict in the Republic of Angola continues to be a source of
great concern to my government."
</P>
<P>
He said "UNITA-Savimbi's intransigence, as we all know, is
responsible for the collapse of the 1994 Lusaka peace protocol on
Angola."
</P>
<P>
"This sad development denied us of yet another golden
opportunity that should have brought about lasting peace to
Angola," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sampa called on all peace-loving countries to continue and
intensify renewed efforts to realize peace in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The cost of war to the Angolan people in terms of loss of human
life, forced migrations and economic development is one that can
not be redeemed, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Similarly, we in Zambia have paid a high price for the war not
only in terms of the loss of lives of our people and the
displacement of those in the vicinity of the common border, but
also in terms of handling the refugee problem," the Zambian
minister said.
</P>
<P>
It is with these realities, he said, Zambia fully supports the
U.N.- imposed sanctions against UNITA led by Jonas Savimbi and all
other initiatives taken under the auspices of the Organization of
African Unity and the Southern African Development Community to
resolve the protracted conflict.
</P>
<P>
Sampa assured Angola that his country will do all it can to
deny UNITA- Savimbi and his war machinery territorial transit
facilities for its logistical shipments.
</P>
<P>
He urged the participants of the session to consider any other
measures that the two countries can take to help put an end to the
wanton destruction of human life and property in Angola
perpetrated by UNITA- Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Angolan Home Affairs Minister Fernando
Dos Santos said the best way to remove obstacles between the sides
is dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He called for joint efforts to sort out the obstacles and
promote closer bilateral relations, stressing that his country
will honor its commitment to ensuring security on the common
border area.
</P>
<P>
Angola has accused Zambia of allowing its territory to be used
to transport military and logistical supplies to UNITA but the
latter denied the accusation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
