<HEADLINE> U.S. Scholars Identify Top 10 Technologies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Our overall conclusion is that today's wave of technological
change seems destined to transform life over the next 20 to 30
years," writes study director William Halal from George Washington
University in the July-August issue of The Futurist magazine.
</P>
<P>
Among the top-ten-techology list for the next decade are:
</P>
<P>
--Portable information appliances rival PCs.
</P>
<P>
--Fuel-cell powered cars hit the streets.
</P>
<P>
--Precision farming becomes ultra-efficient.
</P>
<P>
--Millions of consumers buy customized merchandise online
instead of visiting stores.
</P>
<P>
--Teleliving becomes the lifestyle of choice by 2010.
</P>
<P>
--Virtual assistants handle routine chores.
</P>
<P>
--Genetically designed species of plants and animals enter the
mainstream by 2008.
</P>
<P>
--Computers take over health care tasks.
</P>
<P>
--Alternative energy challenges carbon-based fuels.
</P>
<P>
--Smart robots take on sophisticated jobs.
</P>
<P>
The GW Forecast of emerging technologies began in 1990. The
ongoing project to identify forthcoming breakthroughs in
technology and strategically plan for their impact is now online
at GWForecast.gwu.edu/. 
