<HEADLINE> Ruling Party Candidate Promises to Promote Mexico's International Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) presidential candidate Francisco
Labastida promised Saturday that if he wins Sunday's elections he
will "deepen" Mexico's relations with Latin America, especially
with Central America, and with the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Some hours before the crucial presidential elections, the most
competed for in the history of the country, Labastida said that
his government would promote "areas of wider development with
Central America," including not only trade , but also the fields
of culture and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Relations with Central America will be "a prioritary area" for
Mexico in his government, said Labastida.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government he will preside will develop "very
close relations" with Latin American countries, including Cuba. "
We would seek to strengthen them."
</P>
<P>
Labastida met Saturday morning at a Mexico City hotel with
donzens of correspondents and special envoys from various
countries who will cover the elections.
</P>
<P>
The PRI candidate also mentioned Mexico's relations with the
United States and Canada, its partners since 1994 in the North
America Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
He said he will expand the relations with the United States and
Canada, " and go on to fields still not touched," but he did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the relations his government would develop with
other countries, Labastida said that he would expand the ties of
Mexico with Russia, Japan, and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Labastida, convinced that he will win Sunday's elections, even
forecast he would defeat his closest rival by a margin of two
million votes.
</P>
<P>
Labastida faces Vicente Fox, the candidate of the extreme right
opposition Alliance for Change, led by the National Action Party (
PAN), in the most fierce fighting of the Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
The Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) took power in 1929,
with opinion polls predicting a neck and neck race between the PRI
's Francisco Labastida and conservative candidate Vicente Fox.
</P>
<P>
The almost 59 million eligible voters are also called upon to
choose a new 500-member Congress, replace 128 Senators, elect
three state governors and pick a new mayor for Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
The center-left Party of the Democratic Revolution (PRD), whose
presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas runs a distant third in
opinion polls, appears certain to retain the government of the
Mexican capital, while the PRI is unlikely to regain the
congressional majority it lost in 1996. 
</P>
