<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Bill to Ban Secret Political Contribution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday signed legislation to ban unlimited secret political
contributions.
</P>
<P>
The law "will help clean up the system by forcing organizations
to come clean about their donors," Clinton said on the White House
's South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the law as the first new restriction on political money
in 20 years, Clinton said Congress should move quickly to use it
as a building block for comprehensive campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good law, an I thank everyone for voting for it,"
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, which passed the Senate Thursday by a vote of
92-6, addressed the U.S. Tax Code known as Section 527, which
permitted tax-exempt groups to use hidden, undisclosed donors to
pay for advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Citing an organization called Citizens for Better Medicare as
example, Clinton said the organization "has flooded the airwaves
with negative ads."
</P>
<P>
He also said some private-interest organizations such as
pharmaceutical companies, trying to influence the debate over a
prescription drug benefit for older Americans, could "pour
millions of dollars into these efforts while keeping citizens in
the dark."  
</P>
</TEXT>
