<HEADLINE> S. Africa Considers Evacuating Penguins From Polluted Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- South African authorities are
considering the evacuation of 55,000 penguins from Dassen Island
in Western Cape after the island was polluted by oil spill.
</P>
<P>
Schalk Carstens, deputy-director of disaster management in
Western Cape, said on Saturday that a meeting would be held soon
to discuss the latest development.
</P>
<P>
He said all the penguins affected by last Friday's oil spill
from the bulk oil carrier, Treasure, were being evacuated on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"But at this stage the clean birds are still remaining on the
island," he said.
</P>
<P>
Carstens said although it was a "very bad situation",
everything was still under control, adding: "We are closely
monitoring the situation."
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists held that it might not be necessary to
evacuate the birds off Dassen Island.
</P>
<P>
They have been fenced in to prevent them leaving the island and
entering the sea after oil from the sunken Treasure encircled the
island.
</P>
<P>
An aerial picture taken in the vicinity of the island showed
that strong sea currents and the wind appeared to be causing the
oil slick to drift past the island.
</P>
<P>
A change in weather conditions -- which was likely -- could
result in the oil being blown away from the island and then the
pollution would not be as bad as feared earlier.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 penguins had so far been taken off Dassen
Island and were being rehabilitated in Salt River.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the South African National Foundation for the
 Conservation of Coastal Birds, Christina Pretorius, said 400
penguin chicks were being cared for at a private sanctuary in
Melkbosstrand on the Cape West coast where they would be hand-fed
and reared. A further 94 chicks were being cared for in a separate
facility in Milnerton.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a second batch of 160 penguins was trucked overnight
to Port Elizabeth and released into the sea in Algoa Bay on
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
