<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Urges African Unity for Fair Global Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa has urged African countries to stand together in demanding
for a more just trade and investment regime so as to participate
effectively in the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an official dinner hosted for visiting Namibian
President Sam Nujoma in Dar es Salaam on Saturday, Mkapa said
there is no way a poor African country can, on its own, face the
challenge of the process under an unfair world economic order.
</P>
<P>
"Our only hope is in standing together. United we stand,
divided we fall. We must not waver from demanding a more just
world trade and investment regime no matter how formidable the
odds," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He warned that given the ever widening wealth gap between the
rich and the poor, African countries are standing higher chances
of being net losers in the evolving world trade regime.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, at the beginning of the 20th
century, the wealth gap between developing and industrialized
world was one U.S. dollar to nine U.S. dollars, while at the end
of the century, it widened disproportionately to one U.S. dollar
to 65 U.S. dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said Africa received marginal interest by foreign
investors and he wondered if there is sufficient political will in
governments of rich countries to facilitate the transfer of a fair
share of technology and production activities to Africa.
</P>
<P>
He cited last year when Africa, including South Africa,
received only 11 billion U.S. dollars or 1.3 percent of the 827
billion U.S. dollars inward investment in the world.
</P>
<P>
That is why African countries must stand together and help each
other and increase the speed at which they share experiences and
facilities and integrate their economies, said Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
On democracy, he said there is no uniformity in the entire
world and stressed the need for African countries, like other
countries elsewhere, to continuously seek to improve democracy and
governance in accordance with its own history and circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"Some of those who today appear so intolerant of the
imperfections of African democracy have conveniently forgotten
that when they colonized us, they permit us no right to vote at
all," Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
He condemned the attempts during the recent Zimbabwean
parliamentary elections to vilify the contribution of those who
fought for the freedom of that country and its people, saying such
move is an insult to not only Zimbabwean freedom fighters, but
those who worked hard to rid all of Southern Africa of colonialism
and racist minority rule.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Nujoma arrived here Saturday for a three-day
state visit during which he will officially open the 24th Dar es
Salaam International Trade Fair on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
