<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chretien Hails Stronger Economy on Canada Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien hailed stronger economy in decades under his government
Saturday, while the country is celebrating its 133rd birth day.
</P>
<P>
"It is a time of boundless opportunity. Our economy is
stronger than its has been in decades," said the prime minister at
the national day celebration attended by more than 70,000 people
in the capital city Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
He also took the opportunity to congratulate Canadians for the
country to be recently chosen "as the best country in the world in
which to live" by the United Nations for the seventh straight year.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to hold "unshakable commitment" to sharing prosperity
while ensuring "no Canadian is left behind."
</P>
<P>
Canada Day is also blessed by nation-wide tax cuts that involve
about 15 million taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
Under the government's tax reduction plan taking effect
Saturday,an average family of four with two incomes totalling 60,
000 Canadian dollars (about 40,541 U.S. dollars) will save a
monthly 38 dollars(about 26 U.S. dollars), which will rise to 42
dollars (about 28 U.S.dollars) a month next year.
</P>
<P>
A single-income family of four with 60,000 Canadian dollars in
annual income will save 81 dollars (about 55 U.S. dollars) a month
this year and about 84 dollars (about 57 U.S. dollars) a month
next year.
</P>
<P>
The tax changes are the first stage of a five-year package
designed to cut income taxes by 58 billion Canadian dollars (about
39 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
